==Spanish==

===Etymology===
Origin {{unk|es|uncertain}}.<ref>{{cite-web|en|url=https://blog.oup.com/2014/06/baron-etymology-word-origin-part-2/|title=A globalized history of “baron,” part 2|date=2014-06-18|accessdate=2021-02-09|work=OUPblog}}</ref> First attested as {{inh|es|LL|bā̆rō}} in the 5th century [[w:Salic Law|Salian Law]], meaning "man". It appears as such in other Germanic laws (as {{m|la|barus}} in Alemannic ones) and is later glossed by [[w:Isidore|Isidore]] (Or. 9.4.31) as "mercenary soldier". The original meaning could have been "man", especially in relation to some one else, as in "the king's man," passing on one side into "servant, vassal," on another into "man as opposed to slave, freeman," also as opposed to wife "husband," as opposed to female "male."<ref>{{R:OED|baron}}</ref> It could derive:
* from {{der|es|gem-pro|*barō}} via {{bor|es|frk|*barō}}, perhaps from {{der|gl|ine-pro|*bʰer-||to bear}}, with the most semantically or formally convincing Germanic cognate being {{cog|ang|beorn||man, warrior}}, itself of uncertain origin;
* from {{der|es|gem-pro|*warō|t=protector}}, {{m|gem-pro|*warōną||to watch, protect}}, as has been suggested by George G. Nicholson. The borrowing of /w/ as /b/ instead of /gw/, as in {{m|es|guardar}}, would be irregular;
* some relation to Classical {{inh|es|la|bārō||dunce, lout}} and {{m|la|bardus|t=stupid}}, both of unknown etymology, is still possible.
{{doublet|es|barón}}. Cognate to {{cog|pt|varão}}, {{m|pt|barão}}, {{cog|gl|varón}}, {{m|gl|barón}}, {{cog|fr|baron}}, {{cog|it|barone}}.

